Question: What improvements would you like to see in these cultural funding programs?

Response ID: resp_1943
Response Text: First I would like to see improvements that are the result of an actual planning process that includes ALL affected parties and is open and professionally developed.  This survey and process are sham attempts to justify and result that has been decided behind closed doors and without participation of the groups affected.  Then if an acceptable process is engaged in, I would say make improvements but stop re-imagining them every couple of years.  Growth and sustainability of arts programming depends on cobbling together funding from many sources, some of which are not accessible at all for certain cultures or certain types of art or certain groups that are "too new" or "too unknown."  The city funds are unique in having a guaranteed source, even though the amounts may rise or fall during certain economies.  If whole groups are whipsawed by being encouraged to grow and develop only to be faced with unattainable requirements such as hard matches or funding pauses, there will be only what we have historically seen - a few well funded major institutions that work hard to get their funding but have strong support from business and political leaders along side a small, endangered group that will never in our lifetimes get the "conservative" funding from businesses and foundations.  They will fight hard to develop and become sustainable, but they don't start from the same starting point and they will die off without dependable support.  Treating both groups the same is on its face inequitable.  Funding should address the needs to groups that are not comparable in ways that are appropriate to their history, strength, cultural reach, and artistic competence.  To make significant changes without engagement from the affected communities is unacceptable - the improvement that I would like to see if less political interference and more actual support for the incredible variety and artistic value that blesses Austin.

